1.en: Written by Jonathan Bristow (Twilighte) in 1992 and released by Mirage Software. This is a homebrew version of the Windows classic for the Oric.

2.en:
The object of the game is to collect and return to the boat as much treasure as possible.

Collect pearls, rare minerals, gold bars and diamonds. Avoid the ocean inhabitants, the octopus creatures and the strange floating yellow sea urchin. If you run out of air while underwater, you'll die, so look out for for the spare scuba tanks to replenish your supply.

Whereas the ZX Spectrum version resembles an arcade-adventure, the Oric version feels more like an arcade game.

Written by Ronald Jeffs in 100% machine code.

3.en:
Following their defeat at the hands of the Xenon fleet the Zorgons have captured the Xenon princess Roz, and have imprisoned her in their castle. You are commissioned to rescue her by scouring the four corners of the Zorgon Empire to capture the magic stones. These stones, guarded by the Quadnogs, Terrapods and many other strange beasts, are needed to bridge the bottomless chasm surrounding the castle, enabling you to achieve your goal.

Each one of the many varied stages in this scintillating mission will test your arcade ability as never before.

4.en:
For the 48K Oric 1 from SOFTEK.

How did I get into this mess? The scanners revealed no sentient life in this sector, when, ZAP! .... I find myself enclosed by forcefields, trapping me in a ring of space with the warships of Gor materialising from nowhere! Superb original all-action game with smooth Hi-Res graphics, superb sound effects, twelve different types of aliens and nine levels of play! 100% machine code .... An absolute must for every 'arcade action' fan with an Oric 1.

Written by Steven Chapman.

It is a version of the arcade game Omega Race.

5.en:
In the year 3000 the gaming grids are dominated by the human/machine hybrids known as Cyborgs. As the newest achievement of the cybernetic sciences, your final testing demands that you battle, and defeat, the most dangerous robotics in the universe. Deadly enemies converge on you as you frantically fire your arm pistol. As you clear each arena, your opponents move faster, take more hits, and mutate into additional nightmarish creations.

A Robotron style game for the 16K or 48K Oric-1 and Oric Atmos. Written by Rita Jay.

6.en:
Elektro Storm is a 1983 version of Missile Command for the Oric-1 and Oric Atmos 48K computers. It was published by PSS and written by Tony Stoddart.

It was also available for the ZX Spectrum, that version being written by Stanley Cartwright.

7.en:
Fairly basic but fast-paced version of Galaxian for the 48K Oric 1.

Written by Gordon Russell

8.en: A version of the arcade game Scramble for the Oric-1 and Oric Atmos computers. Released by Orpheus and programmed by John Cumming, Gary Munroe and Ian Marshall.
